The radiance ofvirtue and of happiness,tl1e two things most to be desired, dawns upon us later, and far later still comes a full understanding of their nature. ‘ Happy the man‚’ Plato well says, ‘ who even in old age has the good fortune to be able to achieve wisdom and true opinions.’a Therefore since enough has been said about the primm-y goods of nature, let us now consider the more important things that follow later. In generating and developing the human body, Nature’s procedure was to make some parts perfect at birth, and to fashion other parts as it grew up, without making much use of external and artificial aids.
